## 2. Layered (N-Tier) Architecture

Application divided into **horizontal layers**, each with a distinct responsibility. Each layer only communicates with the layer directly below it.

```
+----------------------------+
|    PRESENTATION LAYER      |  <- UI / API
+----------------------------+
|    APPLICATION LAYER       |  <- Use cases
+----------------------------+
|     BUSINESS LAYER         |  <- Rules
+----------------------------+
|    PERSISTENCE LAYER       |  <- ORM
+----------------------------+
|     DATABASE LAYER         |  <- SQL/NoSQL
+----------------------------+
```

| Property | Value |
|---|---|
| Deployment | Layered units |
| Scalability | Limited |
| Testability | High |

**When to use:** Enterprise apps, well-defined separation of concerns.

---

## 3. Microservices Architecture

Application broken into **small, independent services**, each responsible for a specific business capability. Communicate over network (HTTP/REST, gRPC, messaging).

```
       +---------+
       | Client  |
       +----+----+
            |
       +----v----+
       | API GW  |
       +-+---+--++
         |   |   |
    +----v-+ | +--v---+
    |UserSvc| | |Order |
    +---+---+ | +-+----+
        |  +--v--+  |
        |  |PaySvc|  |
        |  +------+  |
   +----v--+    +----v-+
   |  DB 1 |    | DB 2 |
   +-------+    +------+
```

| Property | Value |
|---|---|
| Deployment | Independent per service |
| Scalability | High (per service) |
| Complexity | Very High |
| Coupling | Low |

**Examples:** Netflix, Amazon, Uber

**When to use:** Large teams, independent deployments, diverse technology stacks.

