## 4. Service-Oriented Architecture (SOA)

Similar to microservices but services are **coarser-grained** and communicate through an Enterprise Service Bus (ESB). Services are reusable business units shared across the enterprise.

```
+--------+    +--------+    +--------+
|ServiceA|    |ServiceB|    |ServiceC|
+----+---+    +----+---+    +---+----+
     +-----------v-----------+
          +----v-------+
          |     ESB     |
          +-----+-------+
     +-----------^-----------+
+---v---+  +----v---+  +---v---+
|Consumer|  |Consumer|  |Consumer|
+--------+  +--------+  +--------+
```

**When to use:** Enterprise integration, legacy system coordination, cross-team service reuse.

---

## 5. Serverless Architecture (FaaS)

Business logic runs in **stateless functions** triggered by events. Infrastructure management is fully abstracted — pay-per-invocation.

```
  +------+   +------+   +------+
  | HTTP |   |Queue |   |Timer |
  |Trig. |   |Trig. |   |Trig. |
  +--+---+   +--+---+   +--+---+
     |           |          |
  +--v---+   +---v---+  +---v---+
  |Lambda |  | Lambda | | Lambda |
  | FuncA |  | FuncB  | | FuncC  |
  +-------+  +--------+ +--------+
     |           |          |
  +--v-----------v----------v--+
  |       Cloud Services       |
  |    (S3, DynamoDB, etc.)   |
  +----------------------------+
```

| Property | Value |
|---|---|
| Cost model | Pay-per-invocation |
| Scalability | Auto / infinite |
| Vendor lock-in | High |

**When to use:** Variable workloads, event-driven tasks, teams with no ops capacity.

