## 12. Space-Based Architecture

Designed for **extreme scalability**. Removes the database as a bottleneck using an in-memory distributed data grid.

```
+----------------------------------+
|        PROCESSING UNITS          |
| +---------+   +---------+        |
| | PU 1    |   | PU 2    |  ...   |
| |(app +   |   |(app +   |        |
| | cache)  |   | cache)  |        |
| +---------+   +---------+        |
+-----------+----------------------+
            |
+-----------v-----------+
| Virtualized Middleware |
|(Messaging, Data Grid) |
+------------------------+
```

**When to use:** High-traffic apps, trading platforms, gaming backends.

---

## 13. Broker / Message Bus Architecture

Central broker **routes messages** between components. Components only know the broker, not each other.

```
+--------+    +-----------------+    +--------+
|Service |--->|  Message Broker |--> |Service |
|   A    |    |(RabbitMQ/Kafka) |    |   B    |
+--------+    +--------+--------+    +--------+
                       |
                  +----v----+
                  |Service C|
                  +---------+
```

**When to use:** Decoupled services, asynchronous workflows, event fan-out.

---

## 14. Peer-to-Peer (P2P) Architecture

No central server — every node is **both client and server**. Nodes share resources directly.

```
    +-----+        +-----+
    |Node |<------>|Node |
    +--+--+        +--+--+
       |   +-----+    |
       +-->|Node |<---+
           +-----+
```

**Examples:** File sharing (BitTorrent), blockchain (Bitcoin, Ethereum)

**When to use:** Decentralized systems, blockchain networks, file sharing.

---

## 15. Client-Server Architecture

Clients request services, servers provide them. The **most fundamental** distributed architecture pattern.

```
 +--------+   request   +--------+
 | Client |------------>| Server |
 |        |<------------|        |
 +--------+   response  +--------+
```

**Variants:**
- **2-Tier:** Client ↔ Server
- **3-Tier:** Client ↔ App Server ↔ DB Server
- **N-Tier:** Multiple intermediary layers

---

## 16. Master-Slave Architecture

Master node **delegates work** to slave nodes and aggregates results. Used for replication and parallel computation.

```
           +--------+
           | Master |
           +----+---+
    +-------+   |   +-------+
 +--v--+    +--v--+    +--v--+
 |Slave|    |Slave|    |Slave|
 |  1  |    |  2  |    |  3  |
 +-----+    +-----+    +-----+
```

**Examples:** MySQL primary-replica, Redis replication, Hadoop MapReduce

---

## 17. Shared-Nothing Architecture

Each node is **fully independent** with its own CPU, memory, and disk. No shared state — perfect for horizontal scaling.

```
+--------------+  +--------------+  +--------------+
|   Node 1     |  |   Node 2     |  |   Node 3     |
| CPU+RAM+DB   |  | CPU+RAM+DB   |  | CPU+RAM+DB   |
+--------------+  +--------------+  +--------------+
        No shared resources between nodes
```

**Examples:** Cassandra, CockroachDB, Google Spanner

