## 18. Lambda Architecture (Big Data)

Handles massive data with **two parallel paths**: Batch layer (historical) + Speed layer (real-time), merged at Serving layer.

```
              +-------------------+
Data -------->|   BATCH LAYER     |---> Batch Views
Stream        +-------------------+          |
  |                                          v
  |          +-------------------+    +----------+
  +--------->|   SPEED LAYER     |--->| SERVING  |--> Query
             +-------------------+    |  LAYER   |
             Real-time Views          +----------+
```

**When to use:** Analytics platforms, large-scale ETL, Hadoop + Storm pipelines.

---

## 19. Kappa Architecture (Big Data)

Simplified Lambda — **removes the batch layer**. All processing through a single streaming pipeline. Historical data reprocessed by replaying the stream.

```
Data Stream --> [Stream Processing] --> Serving Layer --> Query
                    (Kafka+Flink)
                         |
                 Replayable Log
               (replay = recompute)
```

**When to use:** When Lambda is too complex; stream-first systems.

---

## 20. Data Mesh Architecture

Treats **data as a product** with domain teams owning their own data pipelines. Decentralized data ownership following microservices principles.

```
+----------------------------------------+
|         DOMAIN-ORIENTED DATA           |
|                                        |
| +------------+ +------------+ +------+ |
| |   Team A   | |   Team B   | |Team C| |
| |(Owns data) | |(Owns data) | |(Own) | |
| +-----+------+ +-----+------+ +--+---+ |
|       |              |           |     |
|       +--------------+-----------+     |
|                      |                 |
|          +-----------v----------+      |
|          | Self-Serve Platform  |      |
|          +---------------------+      |
+----------------------------------------+
```

**When to use:** Large orgs with multiple data domains and autonomous teams.

---

## 21. Microfrontend Architecture

Applies microservices thinking to the **frontend**. Each team owns a vertical slice including UI — independently deployable.

```
+--------------------------------------+
|         SHELL / CONTAINER            |
| +---------+ +---------+ +---------+ |
| | Team A  | | Team B  | | Team C  | |
| | (Cart)  | |(Product)| | (Auth)  | |
| | React   | |  Vue    | | Svelte  | |
| +---------+ +---------+ +---------+ |
+--------------------------------------+
```

**When to use:** Large frontend teams needing independent deployment and tech flexibility.

---

## 22. JAMstack Architecture

**JavaScript + APIs + Markup.** Pre-rendered static sites served from CDN with dynamic features via JavaScript and APIs.

```
Build Time:
Content --> SSG --> HTML/JS/CSS --> CDN

Runtime:
Browser --> CDN (static)
Browser --> API (dynamic)
```

**Tools:** Next.js, Gatsby, Netlify, Vercel

**When to use:** Marketing sites, blogs, docs, e-commerce storefronts.

---

## 23. BFF — Backend for Frontend

**Dedicated backend per frontend type** (mobile, web, TV). Each BFF is optimized for its specific client's needs.

```
              +-------------+
Mobile App -->|  Mobile BFF |
              +------+------+
                     |
Web App -------->+---v-------+    +-----------+
                 |  Web BFF  |--> |  Backend  |
                 +------+----+    |  Services |
                     |            +-----------+
Smart TV ------->+---v------+
                 |  TV BFF  |
                 +----------+
```

**When to use:** Multiple client types with different data shapes and performance requirements.

---

## 24. SAGA Pattern Architecture

Manages **distributed transactions** across microservices without 2PC. Sequence of local transactions with compensating transactions for rollback.

```
Choreography (event-based):
OrderSvc--event-->PaySvc--event-->StockSvc--event-->ShipSvc

Orchestration (central coordinator):
     +-------------------+
     | Saga Orchestrator |
     +--+------+------+--+
      cmd     cmd    cmd
     +---+  +----+  +-----+
     |Pay|  |Stck|  |Ship |
     +---+  +----+  +-----+
```

**When to use:** Distributed transactions, multi-service workflows, e-commerce order flows.

---

## 25. Strangler Fig Architecture

**Migration pattern** to incrementally replace a legacy monolith with microservices. New functionality goes into microservices; old code is strangled over time.

```
Phase 1:  Client --> Monolith (all traffic)

Phase 2:  Client --> Facade --> Monolith (most)
                            +-> New Service (some)

Phase 3:  Client --> Facade --> New Services (all)
```

**When to use:** Legacy modernization without big-bang rewrites.

---

## 26. Cell-Based Architecture

System divided into **isolated cells**, each a complete mini-stack (app + DB + cache). Traffic is routed to cells. Failure is contained within a cell.

```
          Load Balancer / Router
         /          |           \
   +---------+  +---------+  +---------+
   | Cell 1  |  | Cell 2  |  | Cell 3  |
   | App+DB  |  | App+DB  |  | App+DB  |
   +---------+  +---------+  +---------+
   User 1-1000  1001-2000     2001-3000
```

**When to use:** High-availability systems, multi-tenant SaaS, blast-radius containment.

---

## 27. Edge Computing Architecture

Processing happens **closer to the user** at network edge (CDN nodes, edge servers) rather than a central data center.

```
User --> Edge Node (nearby) --> Central Cloud (if needed)
         (compute + cache)
```

**Tools:** Cloudflare Workers, AWS Lambda@Edge

**When to use:** IoT devices, low-latency requirements, global content delivery.

---

## 28. Reactive Architecture

Based on the **Reactive Manifesto**: systems are Responsive, Resilient, Elastic, and Message-Driven.

| Principle | Meaning |
|---|---|
| Responsive | Always responds in time |
| Resilient | Stays responsive under failure |
| Elastic | Scales under varying load |
| Message-Driven | Async message passing |

**Tools:** Akka, RxJava, Project Reactor, Vert.x

**When to use:** High-availability systems, financial platforms, streaming applications.

---

## 29. Actor Model Architecture

**Actor** is the fundamental unit of computation. Each actor has its own state, processes messages asynchronously, and can create other actors.

```
 +--------+  msg  +--------+  msg  +--------+
 | Actor  |------>| Actor  |------>| Actor  |
 |   (A)  |       |   (B)  |       |   (C)  |
 +--------+       +--------+       +--------+
 State:{x}        State:{y}        State:{z}
```

**Examples:** Erlang/OTP (WhatsApp), Akka, Microsoft Orleans

**When to use:** Highly concurrent systems, game servers, real-time simulations.

---

## 30. Plugin / Extension Architecture

Core system with a **plugin API** allowing third parties to extend functionality without modifying the core.

```
+----------------------------------+
|            CORE SYSTEM           |
|  +----------------------------+  |
|  |      Plugin Registry       |  |
|  +----------------------------+  |
+----------------------------------+
         |
  +------+--------+
  | Plugin A | Plugin B |
  +----------+----------+
```

**Examples:** VS Code, WordPress, Eclipse, Jenkins

**When to use:** Platforms, IDEs, CMSs, developer tools, marketplaces.

---

## 31. API Gateway Architecture

**Single entry point** for all client requests. Handles routing, auth, rate limiting, SSL termination, monitoring, and caching.

```
       +-----------------------------------------+
Client |              API GATEWAY                |
  +--->| Auth | RateLimit | Logging | SSL | Cache |
       +----+-----+------+----------+----+--------+
            |     |      |          |
         +--v-+ +-v--+ +-v--+    +-v--+
         |SvcA| |SvcB| |SvcC|    |SvcD|
         +----+ +----+ +----+    +----+
```

**When to use:** Microservices, API management, multi-client systems.

---

## 32. Service Mesh Architecture

**Infrastructure layer** for service-to-service communication. Each service gets a sidecar proxy handling traffic, security, and observability.

```
+-------------------+  +-------------------+
|  Service A        |  |  Service B        |
|  +-------------+  |  |  +-------------+  |
|  | App Code    |  |  |  | App Code    |  |
|  +-------------+  |  |  +-------------+  |
|  +-------------+  |  |  +-------------+  |
|  |Sidecar Proxy|<-+--+->|Sidecar Proxy|  |
|  +-------------+  |  |  +-------------+  |
+-------------------+  +-------------------+
          ^                    ^
          +---- Control Plane -+
               (Istio/Linkerd)
```

**When to use:** Large microservice clusters, Kubernetes environments, zero-trust security.

